While almost all motives can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems to be a clear result that only one phone should be purchased.
This means that there are sufficient reasons for obtaining an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end gramophone to put up Maxim Turbulenc's new album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disk, and from the point of view of quality there is no objective reason for this to happen.
However, if there are vinyl discs in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you are at least probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, i.e. compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, just like a Pink Floyd fan would have difficulty withholding listeners purchased for 20 crowns in the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is broad.
The life of batteries is also decisive
