A first virtual operator will win Chequia this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in Chequia is relatively advanced, with our operators offering almost the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, on many occasions, the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Office, which reported that the price of a SMS was higher at home than in the rest of the Union, confirmed that.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming royalties regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of cheaper Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Chequia remain so high in comparison to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÄ), who has repeatedly stated that in Chequia there was no place for another operator, is choking with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently not very lucky (by the way, now it would find it difficult to find frequencies).
There is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable drop in prices, to which the traditional operators had to respond as well.
However, even before the entry of party trouble such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those that are heard today at home were allowed to be heard in Britain.
However, it became apparent that there was room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In only six months, this operator has managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let us add that behind the Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which owns, among other things, the U: fon in Chechen.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need much less customers than a conventional operator.
They are free from relatively high construction, operation and maintenance costs of the mobile network.
For example, virtual operators worldwide are profiling as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in Britain at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, building on an unusual target group can also be a good call for publicity.
This operator is specifically targeted at men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to walk at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone's spokesperson, is in doubt: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services. "
In Chequia, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Chequia, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the successful expansion of this project, but in Chequia the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries of our area, "said in a telephone entretient for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the financial group Penta.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in Chequia are in any case not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their utmost to ensure that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real Telefonika competitor in the field of business customers, has not hid, for a long time enough, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
And the sooner the better.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have been able to move forward in the negotiations, "said the spokesperson for the Pavel Kaidl Group.
The future may therefore be promising.
Unofficial information suggests that we may be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not think there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
For the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us, "said Vlastimil Sršeengen of the Telefonika O2 press department, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is almost excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement. "
Vodafone rather directs his attention to the completion of requests to obtain his own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most input from the point of view of clients.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to discover a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile Internet. "
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profit.
What is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to be understood as a fair larvae. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U: fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on ČTÄ, when the U: fon was created, was that of T-Mobile.
This is reflected by information made available to the public from the ČTÄ web pages.
Today, however, U: fon is ready to be used as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competition in the mobile market has also been recently amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would submit it, and above all its services, to high requirements. "
But given the attitude of mobile operators, the indifference of Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of ČTÄ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately has no power in Chequia to intervene in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
In the face of this problem, however, he adopted his typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at this time, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not, a priori, been of sufficient interest to conventional operators, "said in response to our question Kristián Chalupa of the ÚOHS Department of External Relations.
A declaration made in this way would not surprise representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an Office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a declaration is more than disgusting.
All the more so as Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services."
Pressure for the fair functioning of the market and for lower prices is apparently not part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which is the result of their reactions.
The question, if this is really a chance, arises naturally.
Similarly, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the random and hard fight of competition.
"In this regard, the Office has not identified signs of anti-competitive behaviour, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and none therefore has an increased corresponding responsibility for its behaviour in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably not even available to the telecommunications regulator, "said Chaloupa in his statement.
One of the many points of discord is the interpretation of the dominant position in the market.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÄ, according to which telecommunications is, from an economic point of view, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position in such a market.
However, some law experts offer another vision: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on his network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators operate visibly in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Reflecting responsibility over the ČTÄ is a rather common turn in communications, through which the ÚOHS washes its hands on the case.
We have already met this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the new telecommunication law, recently adopted, was not successful in expanding the powers of ČTÄ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This means that the representatives of the ÚOHS must know very well, but their interests appear to be elsewhere.
When no one's looking, it can work.
However, the operation of some kind of virtual pseudo operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price list for mobile telephone services, but they are only in part public.
In most cases, there is a question of firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
For example, special mobile services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms generally reach only elected members.
The magic tower consists of the fact that the company is in front of the operator figure of a conventional customer company, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important client, she gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are talking about happens, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would examine and which could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the company in question," answered our question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is rather unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not been reached to the managers of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, it may be thousands of customers.
Auncun operator, however, does not rule against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them significant benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický states the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a percentage of customers negligible.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully have it, in the way of ordinary customers of mobile operators. "
This is precisely what should seem strange at ČTÄ.
In addition, there is another question to the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers in order to be able to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to be content with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable drop in service prices.
However, virtually in all countries where virtual operators appeared, traditional operators were trying, sometimes more, or less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were almost the same - a market too small or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulators in developed countries, who defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers, took place.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they finally obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the form of a hot potato that is disposed of by transmitting it to a close target.
As a result of our experiences, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable to them in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the crack.
If the slippery information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at home, the Czech mobile market may return to movement.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain impassible in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of others.
And we may cease calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national hymn.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The hymn was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is made by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the hymn's arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.czserver.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national singing one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that both singers, as well as the choir, have a good diction, so that we can understand the words, which they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate next year its 175th anniversary.
The song Kde domov můj was first held in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the Theater of States) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse of Savetiers), a Czech original play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet naturally became an integral part of the national hymn.
He remained one of seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
How does the "new" hymn sound?
The pragois public transport (MHD) will introduce, Wednesday, the chip into their ticketing system
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be recorded in the history of Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Pragoise Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will climb in the metro, trams and buses, which, instead of having a paper ticket, will have in their pocket an electronic coupon.
At the moment, the latter is accessible for about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can buy a coupon 30 days or 90 days (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and both have it recorded on their smart card in the information points and offices of Dopravní podnik (the Transport Agency), located in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy coupons by internet on the Dopravní podnik web pages: www.dpp.cz. http: / / www.dpp.cz.
Over four hundred people took advantage of the service during the morning.
Those who are starting to use the online store can definitely forget the guichets at the metro stations, where they had so far to pietinate impatience in long tails in order to get paper tickets.
In fact, they will buy their coupon by internet and will be recorded on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these contact points, there is at the disposal of passengers a window with trained staff, which will help those involved with internet purchase and, in addition, will record the coupon they bought on their card," said the spokesperson for the Martin Opatrný project.
In addition to the libraries, it will also be possible to record electronic coupons on the Opencard in automatic distributors installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, remind the machines to compost the tickets and the passengers may have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be eighty," Opatrný added.
An automate will control the coupon instead of the driver
The automates that will work from tomorrow are easy to use.
Just introduce the Opencard chip card and the coupon previously purchased will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the vicinity of the city.
