Sudetes called for a referendum in the USA
In 1945, Sudanese Germans called for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This is the result of a letter in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the South Bohemian).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudanese Germans allegedly addressed the US President with such a desire.
This is the result of a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov in the letter ask the American President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not in oppressors and enemies, but in liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of Šumava is heartfelt."
Since the rally to Czechoslovakia is presumably promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, untenable attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take into his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for vengeance of "Czech oppressors."
If the President of the USA doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the USA, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text in the letter may, in view of the current knowledge of post-war history, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it clearly illustrates the expectations of Sudanese Germans at the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least see that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them had such a possibility.
Some were waiting for the United States and Great Britain to obtain some kind of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the marine in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, Czech would be beneficial to them," said Chalupa.
None of the German captured who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war felt that, following the Beneš decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
