A rat or a cockroach flee in the face of danger, does that mean that they also feel fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have sensations.
But how could we check that he's feeling the same when he's behaving in the same way as us?
In the online magazine "Edge," contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think you are true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we will enter difficult-to-practice land because Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in front of a danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it does death, leaks or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduct a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make transposition of our experience subjective to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other beings.
At least therefore for these aspects of our conscience that depend on the prefrontal Cortex, among which the conscience of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from other primates.
Another significant particularity could be in the linguistic nature of Man: a large part of his existence being linked to language, it often means that his conscience depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness was not to depend on language, it would probably influence it, so that animal consciousness, regardless of how it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, to analyse on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses us great problems.
