No heels, no ebony clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, free from all tensions to get the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
The other one, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these moments unknown to the general public, where you discover intimate gestures and stolen eyes of artists who do not care to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer blends in "Flamenco - people" the theatrality of some staging with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer reproduces the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flamande Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you should not make pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a unique character.
What I was interested in was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the personality moments of the flamenco stars. "
With the "Song Popular of Mines" festival, Bauer started a long trip in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, remeate classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day."
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captives the public with his art.
The search for essential and magic has been the constant of this work that we present these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
The flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book of collection of portraits exposed to the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsportsportsportsportsportARTproject" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people," the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a moment more or less long.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don't know or who just leave you a few minutes to be able to make them a picture.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas real. "
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, which is called "Flamenco - people," is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 of rue de la Mata (parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule), which will be opened until next October 16.
