The repeats of the alcohol on the wheel will have to install the system 'alcolock'
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative sanctions for alcoholaemia, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting in a drunken state, or if he does not breathe.
The initiative was already announced last June and is now reflected in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project for a year.
Its purpose is to rehabilitate the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State for Road Safety, as well as the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Foundation Technological Institute for Motor Vehicle Safety, will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a drunken state, take over the car.
The alcolock would avoid this because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol rate in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before; or when the alcohol rate of the driver is higher than that allowed.
The cost is greater than EUR 1 000 and is borne by the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device were reducing up to 65% of the offences during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people every year.
This measure is based only on administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with these behaviours before they turn into criminal offences.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means, but reform by criminal means requires reform of the organic law.
The scheme is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one for experimental purposes.
The Congress of Deputies will vote for an initiative by the Spanish Socialist Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses as it has been done in France.
