Speak in sleep
A few children speak during the night.
I do not relate to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who speak during their sleep.
The first time that happens it can surprise you, but in fact it doesn't matter.
It's a benign alteration of sleep called somniloganda.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking at night.
This phenomenon may appear in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or in a more periodic way (daily, once a week, once a month...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often linked to other sleep changes such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (pee in bed) or somnambulism, but this is not always the case.
As we have already said, they can also be associated with very strong fevers, stress or overrexcitation situations.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that has not been studied.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a little quiet voice, with isolated words, murmures or on the contrary with screams, crying, long speeches...
In case somniloganda becomes very frequent, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to obtain an explanation for this problem.
We said it is a benign alteration, that is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another deterioration of sleep that can be treated (for example, if it is related to a apnea of sleep or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore looking for quiet games and avoiding programs or television series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm inside.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as somniloquies appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless for the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he's talking, he's asleep and resting.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), don't have the temptation to question him for information.
You will not get anything, because by sleeping, he is not conscious to be able to organize his thought.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so pay attention to the way you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can question him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts just a few minutes.
