Interview - Blood has become safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Héma-Québec has become one of the world's most secure and effective blood providers.
Most importantly, he reconquered the public's confidence that had been seriously shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada established a public investigation, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from occurring again.
While Justice Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has completed this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," said Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
With efforts to improve the safety of blood and field work products during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence, "she said before proudly asserting that in early 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Decary keeps in mind that "confidence is something extremely fragile."
From its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there were many cases of human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one that has been holding the fort since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when we do not know it and a serious disease may result from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had stayed in the United Kingdom more than a month since 1980 was therefore refused.
A few years ago, however, it was unquestionably shown that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode has shown us that the precautionary principle that has been applied has meaning. "
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique was found in the market: Nucleic Acid (NAT) tests that directly detect the presence of the virus itself and not of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used to date were based.
The NTAs have shortened the mute period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, says the specialist.
This period was reduced to less than one week.
This has significantly reduced the risk that some donors will be infected without knowledge and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of acquiring AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product survives.
I think we can feel comfortable today to receive or prescribe blood transfusion to recover health, "says Héma-Québec's Chief Executive Officer.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen is going to emerge in the system.
No later than last year has appeared on the island of the Meeting the Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant, "says Dr. Decary before we point out that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for adequate supply.
"Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
As anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet recharge.
The aging population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
A healthy person who is 18 years of age and older who meets the eligibility criteria can give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is present, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and cannot give their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to retain them and to encourage them to become a regular donor.
As today's life is so frightened, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving from his blood, "Francine Decary discloses.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye globes and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cordon blood bank in Quebec.
The ombilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, has a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the bank of our millionth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand of it a year.
We should start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year, "says Dr. Decary, who describes this cordon blood collection program as very popular.
"Several mamans are disappointed to be unable to access it," as Héma-Québec has no means of offering this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
