Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Following an orwellian logic, he states that the world's largest gold company has instituted a six million defamation prosecution against three authors and a small publishing house without the sou in order to launch a "transparent public debate."
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dare to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable money in order to prepare for their defence and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost shallow pockets of the mining.
The tactics, in these unequal struggles, are often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will build the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who oses to reconsider this issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are normally done through the exchange of ideas rather than through mackerel.
It was therefore enough for the mining industry to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent research teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and dismisses petitions and letters of support to Black Canada's authors from hand to hand.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while disregard the opinions of that same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to publicly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public who supports Black Canada's authors and publishers does so first of all because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear and judge Barrick, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, not in the context of what many people perceive as a follow-up (continuing the "public debate," Barrick Gold has also just filed a call for the authors of Black Canada to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's overreal speech, Barrick Gold's pursuit is a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the quest for truth, which is essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to quote credible sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that dislike the rich companies in this world in a country like Canada, subject to repetition, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by Black Canada authors.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate pursuit clearly shows that, unlike what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss to the academic world, as well as to the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the Congress leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both chambers of Congress.
It provides for, inter alia, better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of the public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for lack of payment, as well as a right of regard on the wages paid to the leaders of the rescued companies.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House of Representatives President Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards an effective market agreement," said Bush Administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything was done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the current crisis at Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, trauma, chaos and disturbance on the day-to-day lives of the Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned to sprint in recent hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would have on the mood of investors.
The deadline for agreement was the opening of markets this morning.
In late association with the negotiations, the two candidates for the American presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, but not in dissatisfaction with the fact that we are forced to reach this end.
The Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed itself to the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, in particular to allow owners to keep their homes and to the salary of government-rescued business leaders.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no welcome.
