The $700 billion plan is intended to redeem with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risk-effective and invendable claims of US financial institutions.
After 14 months of crisis triggered by the collapse of a real estate bubble which first led to the collapse of risk mortgage credits (subpremiums) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a liquidity freeze and the debandade of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican elected representatives who had put the first draft agreement on hold last week.
It is believed that it has been out of this impasse since the Democrats have accepted that some "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to rounding the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to bear losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its release.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of $250 billion to which will be added $100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
