The psychology of overauction: why are we spending more money?
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Neurology and economics researchers at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the Science magazine, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that's why they prefer even to pay too high a price.
This research has tried to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auction sales.
One of the volunteer groups played the loto, while the other group took part in a ludic auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance process (MMR), researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, one essential element of which is the overauction of a third party, the whole being under the brain trunk, called striatum, was intensively moving during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak in the face of the violent reaction of striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial monitoring analyses.
In these cases, three groups were overcrowded by a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus carried out their placement.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were going out to win the game, then they would receive an additional $15 in reward.
While the third group received those $15 before the auction, the group members also lost that money in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed on victory in one group, while in the other on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the "against failure" team were prepared to put higher than those made by the control group and the "for victory" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation. "- noted Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When do we have to consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the first causes of death.
It is estimated that the Hepatitis Virus patients in Hungary are one hundred miles away, but only seven miles are being treated. This is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are carrying the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to liver-affected infections caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Liver inflammation and yellowness are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, are spread mainly in two forms: Hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g., food or contaminated water), Hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic liquids (semen, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is in any case recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no C. vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the use of contaminated foods, in general, accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible yellowish, the stools become lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing may take two to three weeks.
Every year, around the world, one million people die from the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to reach the virus, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells sadly. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
As a result, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a laboratory routine examination, it is advisable to consult his treating doctor upon the observation of symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be healed, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver, caused by viruses, the causes of its development, and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
