The smart car imitates the flight of the bourdon
What would be the best way to develop technologies that could avoid an obstacle, except for the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the astonishing project presented at the CEATEC, held in Japan, the bees were given the strategic starting idea to Nissan's engineers to inspire them on how they must design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robotic control system, of the BR23C type, which it has equipped with bees qualities, the final objective being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee is its own oval-shaped space, which in reality looks very much like our secure protection hull - explained at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and public technological relations of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays an essential role, as it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers addressed the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, it assesses the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into a avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the bee's movements, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning in an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Contrary to any existing system at present, this avoidance manoeuvre is carried out entirely instinctively.
"If this were not the case, the mini auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," said Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protection envelope, a layer where the collision is considered inevitable at the moment.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a glance.
In contrast to bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonal, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotary movement, acceleration as well as slowing as manoeuvres available to the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses polymer Lithium batteries that are lighter and have a larger energy concentration, making their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the intelligent instinctive reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only treat a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of continuous memory.
We don't need a memory of giga-bytes or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant avoidance technology. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter serial-made cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
