Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Hungarian Central Statistical Office.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to the previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent, compared with the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry have only undergone a small increase in the order of 0.1 per cent from July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastics and chemicals resulted in a considerable monthly increase in the prices of the product and chemical manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
The result was deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), and a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry increased between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent a significant weight in national industrial exploitation, prices were up 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, oil processing prices experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the manufacturing of metallurgical products, there was an increase in prices by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have taken place in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and apparatus (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases have evolved between 0.6 per cent and 9.1 per cent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
The prices of the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Among the internal trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, it was the profit-to-investment initiating sectors that showed the most significant monthly price rise (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material-producing sectors for further processing did not change over the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-generating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment decreased by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
