Today, in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, whose host is France, began as a representative of the current Presidency of the European Union.
In his message to the plenary, as one of the main spokespersons for the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, Member of Parliament for the European People's Party Fidesz, drew attention to segregations in education, because it is a violation of the law that most affects Roma children and therefore one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened on the one hand by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and on the other by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among the people invited to participate in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most eminent representatives of legal protection and European civil bodies, in the field of equal opportunities.
