"An overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have high school degrees, and as a result of poor basic education, only a small party has the opportunity to obtain a higher education degree."
In addition, Járóka stressed that education as the basic right of the human being plays a key role in upholding other fundamental rights.
Investment in early education for Roma children means strengthening the economy of EU member countries.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these reports in the widest possible circle, also between Roma and non-Roma.
The sooner a Roma child starts school, the more likely it is to become a productive member of the labour market; by taxes paid from its income and consumption, it participates in the State budget.
"By their nationality of the European Union, Roma must be assured of their right to quality education, and be protected from low quality and sectarian education." - Lívia Járóka stressed.
According to the Member, objective-oriented collaboration and action by the European Union is necessary for an immediate acceleration of the process of school dissegregation, which is of paramount importance in respect of existing and in preparation anti-discrimination directives.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployed people. We must give the opportunities guaranteed by democracy to Roma children, so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe" - Járóka demanded.
