Listen to full-volume music for an extended period using portable musical devices such as Mp3 readers, can cause permanent hearing lesions.
This is what the European Commission, which in a press release published in Brussels, is announcing the opinion of the Scientific Committee on unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report - let us read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full volume music using portable music devices, for more than one hour a day and a week, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data - continues responsible U- this is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in view of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies. "
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise that they generate.
"The scientists-concluded the executive U- confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now examine with Member States and other interested parties what measures could be adopted to better protect children and adolescents against noise exposure from portable and similar musical devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is increased concern about hearing damage that could derive from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these data using solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Ue Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decimals) for 5 hours per week, exceed current limits on the maximum level of noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This interests 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified around 2.5 and 10 million people in the U.S.
