Students who are victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market does not experience a crisis
According to the last Sunia survey, the tenants' union, rent a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 euros in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 euros in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin must support - explains the head of the Sunia study office, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand on the part of students has distorted the market so much that a process of widespread increase has begun even for residents.
In most cases, the rental offers also contain a series of violations: free-type contracts, unregistered contracts, without rent limits, subleases.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the tax review are necessary to calmer prices.
Listing in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we range from a minimum of 650 euros (Bande Nere zone) to an average value of 800 euros (Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera zone) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria zone)
In Florence, one bed costs an average of 350 / 400 euros, one room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas close to the University, it takes 250 / 280 euros for a double bed, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are requested for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euros for one single) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
We can save only if we move away in the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 euros for a simple one in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed you need 300 / 400 euros, for a simple one, you spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed you have to count 250 / 350 euros, at least 350 for a simple one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rentals are often taken by extra-community students, there is a later anomaly: the rent requested from foreign students is increased by 25 / 30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Adieu old cinema Paradiso, the cities elect the historic rooms.
Historical cinemas close in favour of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it is like a face without eyes"
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore, is a good example of what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the large multihalls, and the death of consumption of mono halls in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that we find ineluctable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historic places and responsible for memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a part of the way and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix de la jurée de Cannes, and that tells the poetry of a province hall, and the nostalgia of a way of living the cinema, lost may be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, mean everything: over the last five years, 316 traditional-type cinemas have closed, and it is the rooms of the main cities that have paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Romaine Emilie is in the lead with 82 mono-halls lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multiroom cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," says Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it is still necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room is closed in a city, these people are not necessarily all willing to go to the multiplex.
Not to mention the misdemeanor of the credit for traders: the State's previous debt is about €10 million.
It is shameful that, from a moral and ethical point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between €16 million and €18 million per year.
The case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which is concerned about these closures, has decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of this kind in Italy, to defend and promote the mono theatres in the historical centres and on the outskirts.
Among the planned standards, there are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the area with limited circulation, and will have special rates for parking and certain parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna setting up other measures.
It is clear, however, that in order to contrast the super power of multiplex, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that for me has always been important: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradiso cinema" to which I have already thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much shared emotions, I turn on the other side to not see the blackened panels by the dust.
